"Abstract One of the best tributes to the use of proper punctuation, is the tale of the untimely end of King Edward II. In 1327, a group of rebellious Welsh barons hired three goons to ‘take out’ King Edward. The latter was promptly whisked away for imprisonment in Berkeley Castle but the goons, fearful for their own lives, would not lift a hand against their monarch without written orders from Queen Isabel’s chief henchman, a bishop who was in on the conspiracy."
